Flatten()¶

The flatten() function is used to get a copy of an given array collapsed into one dimension.

In [1]:
import numpy as np

x = np.array([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]])
x
Out[1]:
array([[1, 2, 3],
       [4, 5, 6]])
In [2]:
x.flatten()
Out[2]:
array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6])
In [3]:
y = np.array([[2,3], [4,5]])
y
Out[3]:
array([[2, 3],
       [4, 5]])
In [4]:
y.flatten()
Out[4]:
array([2, 3, 4, 5])

Find the transpose of a array¶

In [5]:
import numpy as np
a = np.array([[2.,3.],[4.,5.]])
print(a)

[[2. 3.]
 [4. 5.]]
In [6]:
print(a.T)

[[2. 4.]
 [3. 5.]]
In [7]:
arr =  np.random.randint(0,25,(3,3))
arr
Out[7]:
array([[24, 20, 21],
       [ 8, 19, 21],
       [18,  8, 17]])
In [8]:
arr.shape
Out[8]:
(3, 3)
In [9]:
arr.T
Out[9]:
array([[24,  8, 18],
       [20, 19,  8],
       [21, 21, 17]])

[1 2 3]
(3,)
[4 5 6]
(3,)

[1 2 3 4 5 6]

array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6])

(6,)

c1 = np.concatenate((a,b),axis = 0)

Arithmetic Operations¶

You can easily perform array with array arithmetic, or scalar with array arithmetic. Let's see some examples:

In [26]:
data = np.array([1, 2])
ones = np.ones(2)
data + ones
Out[26]:
array([2., 3.])

In [27]:
data - ones
Out[27]:
array([0., 1.])
In [28]:
data * data
Out[28]:
array([1, 4])
In [29]:
data / data
Out[29]:
array([1., 1.])

In [30]:
data**4
Out[30]:
array([ 1, 16])

Broadcasting¶

There are times when you might want to carry out an operation between an array and a single number (also called an operation between a vector and a scalar) or between arrays of two different sizes. For example, your array (well call it data) might contain information about distance in miles but you want to convert the information to kilometers. You can perform this operation with:

In [31]:
data = np.array([1.0, 2.0])
data * 1.6
Out[31]:
array([1.6, 3.2])

In [32]:
data = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4], [5, 6]])
ones_row = np.array([[1, 1]])
data + ones_row
Out[32]:
array([[2, 3],
       [4, 5],
       [6, 7]])

NumPy understands that the multiplication should happen with each cell. That concept is called broadcasting.

In [33]:
np.arange(3)
Out[33]:
array([0, 1, 2])
In [34]:
np.arange(3) + 5
Out[34]:
array([5, 6, 7])
In [35]:
a = np.ones((3,3))
print(a)
print("\n shape:",a.shape)

[[1. 1. 1.]
 [1. 1. 1.]
 [1. 1. 1.]]

 shape: (3, 3)
In [36]:
b = np.arange(3)
print(b)
print("\n shape:",b.shape)

[0 1 2]

 shape: (3,)
In [37]:
a + b
Out[37]:
array([[1., 2., 3.],
       [1., 2., 3.],
       [1., 2., 3.]])
In [38]:
p = np.arange(3).reshape((3,1))
print(p)
print("\n shape:",p.shape)

[[0]
 [1]
 [2]]

 shape: (3, 1)
In [39]:
q = np.arange(3)
print(q)
print("\n shape:",q.shape)

[0 1 2]

 shape: (3,)
In [40]:
p + q
Out[40]:
array([[0, 1, 2],
       [1, 2, 3],
       [2, 3, 4]])

More useful array operations¶

In [41]:
data = np.arange(1,4)
data
Out[41]:
array([1, 2, 3])
In [42]:
data.max()
Out[42]:
3
In [43]:
data.min()
Out[43]:
1
In [44]:
data.sum()
Out[44]:
6

In [45]:
data = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4], [5,6]])
data
Out[45]:
array([[1, 2],
       [3, 4],
       [5, 6]])
In [46]:
data.max()
Out[46]:
6
In [47]:
data.min()
Out[47]:
1
In [48]:
data.sum()
Out[48]:
21

In [49]:
data.max(axis=0)
Out[49]:
array([5, 6])
In [50]:
data.max(axis=1)
Out[50]:
array([2, 4, 6])

Remember that axis 0 is the axis that points downwards, down the rows.

When we use the code np.max(axis = 0) on an array, were effectively telling NumPy to compute the maximum values in that direction the axis 0 direction.

Similarly, remember that in a 2-dimensional array, axis 1 points horizontally. Therefore, when we use NumPy max with axis = 1, were telling NumPy to compute the maxima horizontally, in the axis 1 direction.

Universal Array Functions¶

Numpy comes with many universal array functions, which are essentially just mathematical operations you can use to perform the operation across the array. Let's show some common ones:

In [51]:
import numpy as np

data = np.array([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]])
print(data)

[[1 2 3]
 [4 5 6]]
In [52]:
#Taking square
np.square(data)
Out[52]:
array([[ 1,  4,  9],
       [16, 25, 36]])
In [53]:
#Taking Square Roots
np.sqrt(data)
Out[53]:
array([[1.        , 1.41421356, 1.73205081],
       [2.        , 2.23606798, 2.44948974]])
In [54]:
#Calcualting exponential (e^)
np.exp(data)
Out[54]:
array([[  2.71828183,   7.3890561 ,  20.08553692],
       [ 54.59815003, 148.4131591 , 403.42879349]])

Comparison Operations¶

In [55]:
x = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
x
Out[55]:
array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
In [56]:
x < 3 # less than
Out[56]:
array([ True,  True, False, False, False])
In [57]:
x > 3 # greater than
Out[57]:
array([False, False, False,  True,  True])
In [58]:
x <= 3 # less than or equal to
Out[58]:
array([ True,  True,  True, False, False])
In [59]:
x >= 3 # greater than or equal to
Out[59]:
array([False, False,  True,  True,  True])
In [60]:
x != 3 # not equal
Out[60]:
array([ True,  True, False,  True,  True])
In [61]:
x == 3 # equal
Out[61]:
array([False, False,  True, False, False])

Sorting¶

In [62]:
x = np.array([2, 1, 4, 3, 5])
print(x)

[2 1 4 3 5]
In [63]:
np.sort(x)
Out[63]:
array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
In [64]:
y = np.array([10,20,1,3,45,76])
np.sort(y)
Out[64]:
array([ 1,  3, 10, 20, 45, 76])
In [65]:
np.unique([0,1,2,0,2,3,4,3,0,4,11, 12, 13,13,13,11])
Out[65]:
array([ 0,  1,  2,  3,  4, 11, 12, 13])
